<glossary>
<definition id="fs-idp194754048">
<term>second law of thermodynamics</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp194754688">all spontaneous processes involve an increase in the entropy of the universe</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idp170415152">
<term>standard entropy (<emphasis effect="italics">S</emphasis>°)</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp170416304">entropy for one mole of a substance at 1 bar pressure; tabulated values are usually determined at 298.15 K</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idp85418944">
<term>standard entropy change (Δ<emphasis effect="italics">S</emphasis>°)</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp85420096">change in entropy for a reaction calculated using the standard entropies</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idp90512720">
<term>third law of thermodynamics</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp90513360">entropy of a perfect crystal at absolute zero (0 K) is zero</meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
